t. Using Rumi and contemporary expressions of poetry and whirling associated with him, the book captures the lived reality of Sufism through an ethnographic study of communities in Toronto, Montreal, and Vancouver. Drawing from conversations with Sufi leaders, whirling dervishes, and poets, Merin Shobhana Xavier explores how Sufism is constructed in Canada, particularly at the nexus of Islamic mysticism, Muslim diaspora, spiritual commodity, popular culture, and universal spirituality. Inviting readers with an interest in religion and spirituality, The Dervishes of the North illuminates how non-European Christian traditions, like Islam and Sufism, have informed the religious and spiritual terrain of Canada.  afunded by University of Toronto Libraries  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aSufismzBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 0aSufismzOntariozToronto. 0aSufismzQuebec (Province)zMontreal. 0aSufismzQuébec (Province)zMontréal. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Sufi.2bisacsh  aIslam.  aIslamic mysticism.  aJalal al-Din Rumi.  aMontreal.  aMuslim communities.  aSufism in Canada.  aToronto.  aVancouver.  acontemporary Sufism.  aphilosophy.  apoetry.  apopular spirituality.  areligion.  awhirling dervishes.1 aXavier, Merin Shobhana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aUniversity of Toronto Librariesefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311079736740uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781487552312zOpen Access7040uhttps://www